  1272	## 9. The write log overlay
  1273	
  1274	The overlay gives every atom that needs one a **receipt tape**: an
  1275	append-only (until swept) chain of log records describing recent writes, from
  1276	which the value *as of any world* can be reconstructed. This section covers
  1277	the tape's lifecycle; section 10 covers how reads use it.
  1278	
  1279	### 9.1 When logging happens at all: monotonic activation
  1280	
  1281	`writeMode` is `DIRECT` until the first React root registers with the fork
  1282	(`onRootRegistered`, 6.1), and `LOGGED` from that moment on — permanently.
  1283	One flip per process, never reversed: not at quiescence, not when the last
  1284	component unmounts, not when a root is disposed. The rule has three
  1285	properties worth naming:
  1286	
  1287	- **It cannot race a write.** Root registration (`createRoot`/`hydrateRoot`)
  1288	  strictly precedes any React work being scheduled on that root, and
  1289	  therefore precedes any batch a write could ever need to be excluded from.
  1290	  A write before activation is causally prior to *all* React work — by the
  1291	  time any render pass exists, that write is simply committed history,
  1292	  visible to every pass including `flushSync`, and no schedule can
  1293	  distinguish "it was never logged" from "it was logged and absorbed."
  1294	  Boot-time initialization, module-level setup, tests without React, and
  1295	  benchmarks all live here, at zero overlay cost.
  1296	- **Servers never activate.** Server rendering imports the bindings but
  1297	  registers no client root (`renderToString`/streaming SSR never call
  1298	  `createRoot`), so SSR stays DIRECT for the life of the process — the
  1299	  overlay costs nothing where concurrency cannot exist (13.8).
  1300	- **After activation there is exactly one contract.** Every write in a live
  1301	  React app is logged — urgent or deferred, watcher or no watcher, busy or
  1302	  idle. No secondary mode, no configuration flag, no documented deviation:
  1303	  React lane parity holds unconditionally, and the rest of this document
  1304	  never has to qualify a guarantee with "unless the write happened while
  1305	  idle."
  1306	
  1307	In `LOGGED` mode, **every write is logged**. This mirrors React exactly: a
  1308	`setState` always enqueues an update object; our log record is that update,
  1309	externalized into an arena (and cheaper to allocate). Trying to be cleverer —
  1310	skipping the log for urgent writes when "nothing could tell the difference" —
  1311	is unsound. The proof case: an event handler does an urgent `atom.set(x)`
  1312	while a default-priority batch from earlier in the same event is still
  1313	pending, and then calls `flushSync`. React renders the flushSync work
  1314	*without* the default-priority batch — a legitimate render of a world in
  1315	which the urgent write has happened but the earlier batch has not. If the
  1316	urgent write had skipped the log and gone straight to the canonical value,
  1317	nothing could reconstruct that older world; only a log entry lets the
  1318	flushSync render answer correctly. The same shape reaches even *idle-time*
  1319	writes: a `setTimeout` fires while React has nothing in flight, writes an
  1320	atom, and the watcher broadcast it triggers schedules default-priority
  1321	work — if something then calls `flushSync` in the same task, that render
  1322	legitimately excludes the default batch, and only the write's receipt lets
  1323	the excluded world read the pre-write value the way React's own `useState`
  1324	would. The write and the update it schedules are one causal event split
  1325	across lanes; "no React work was in flight when the write happened" does not
  1326	exempt it. That is why activation is pinned to root registration rather
  1327	than to any measure of React busyness.
  1328	
  1329	**The price, and the pre-registered escape hatch.** The cost of one
  1330	unconditional mode is that timer, socket, and store writes in an idle React
  1331	app pay the logging tax forever: append, tape-creation mark walk on first
  1332	touch, sweep at the next boundary. This document treats that price as a
  1333	number, not a fear — steady logged writes are gated at ≤2× a DIRECT write
  1334	(the entry is ~6 Int32 stores plus one side-array store), tape creation is
  1335	priced per cone size, and LOGGED-idle steady state must hold tier-0 within
  1336	2% (18.2). If those measurements — specifically the tape-creation pricing
  1337	(G-6a) run on a streaming-store workload, sustained external writes with
  1338	React idle — show the tax matters in practice, the pre-registered
  1339	alternative is a *quiescence-gated* write mode (experiment E4, 18.4):
  1340	DIRECT while React has no open or pending work, LOGGED otherwise. That
  1341	design is strictly weaker than this one — the idle-write flushSync schedule
  1342	above becomes unanswerable without a receipt, so a quiescence gate must
  1343	*document* a loose contract (idle writes don't inherit the lane of the
  1344	notification they trigger; a bounded, convergent, one-frame cross-component
  1345	mismatch can paint) rather than claim parity. It is therefore an opt-in
  1346	trade to be made with measurements in hand, not a default.
  1347	
  1348	**Rejected gates, kept as gatekeepers.** (a) *Watcher-count gating* ("log
  1349	only once a watcher is mounted") is unsound: the app's first
  1350	`startTransition(() => { atom.set(1); setShow(true) })` writes before any
  1351	watcher exists, would go DIRECT, and would leave no receipt — so the
  1352	component that mounts *during* that transition's render (13.2's marquee
  1353	case) has no older world to read, and urgent renders leak the transition's
  1354	value. Under monotonic activation this schedule is covered by construction:
  1355	the root registered before the transition could exist, so the write is
  1356	logged. (b) *Quiescence gating presented as exact parity* fails on the
  1357	idle-write flushSync schedule above. Both counterexamples are permanent
  1358	tests (17.6): the E4 experiment — or any future write-mode-gate change —
  1359	must pass the first outright and must either pass the second or replace it
  1360	with an explicitly documented loose contract.
  1361	
  1362	### 9.2 Batch slot interning
  1363	
  1364	Log records need to name their batch in 5 bits. On each logged write:
  1365	
  1366	1. `token = unstable_getCurrentWriteBatch()` (mints lazily inside React).
  1367	2. Look up the slot: a one-entry cache (`lastToken/lastSlot`) catches the
  1368	   common run of writes in one batch; otherwise scan `batchToken[0..31]`
  1369	   (at most 31 live tokens exist — fork invariant 6.2 — so a linear scan of
  1370	   an Int32Array(32) is a handful of nanoseconds).
  1371	3. Miss → claim a free slot (`batchToken[slot] = token`, set bit in
  1372	   `liveSlotMask`, and in `liveDeferredMask` if `token & 1`).
  1373	
  1374	A slot is released (token zeroed, masks cleared) when its batch has retired
  1375	*and* its `batchEntryCount` reaches zero (all entries swept). Because retired
  1376	entries stop consulting their slot (their visibility runs on `RETIRED_SEQ`),
  1377	slot recycling can never mis-attribute an old record.
  1378	
  1379	If all 32 slots are somehow occupied (cannot happen from React's ≤31 live
  1380	tokens; defensive), the engine falls back to treating the write as belonging
  1381	to an always-included pseudo-batch and emits a trace warning — correctness
  1382	degrades toward "urgent" for that write rather than crashing.
  1383	
  1384	### 9.3 Appending a log record
  1385	
  1386	`appendLog(atom, op, payload, applied)`:
  1387	
  1388	```
  1389	if LOG_HEAD == 0:                          // first entry: create the tape
  1390	    base = allocLog()
  1391	    G[base+META] = OP_BASE | RETIRED
  1392	    G[base+SEQ] = ticket()                 // seq of log creation
  1393	    G[base+RETIRED_SEQ] = G[base+SEQ]      // visible to any pass pinned later
  1394	    logVals[base>>2] = values[atom>>2]     // snapshot canonical value
  1395	    LOG_HEAD = LOG_TAIL = base
  1396	    FLAGS |= LOGGED; loggedAtoms.push(atom); loggedAtomCount++
  1397	    notifyWalk(atom, ++walkCounter, /*collect*/ false)  // mark the cone (below)
  1398	rec = allocLog()
  1399	G[rec+META] = op | (slot << 4) | (applied ? APPLIED : 0)
  1400	G[rec+SEQ] = ticket()                      // one global counter, ++ per append
  1401	G[rec+RETIRED_SEQ] = 0
  1402	logVals[rec>>2] = payload
  1403	G[LOG_TAIL+NEXT] = rec; LOG_TAIL = rec
  1404	batchEntryCount[slot]++; if (!applied) unappliedEntries++
  1405	```
  1460	as an ordinary append (9.8).
  1461	
  1462	### 9.4 Applied versus unapplied entries
  1463	
  1464	- A **deferred** write (transition-like, `token & 1`) is *log-only*: the
  1465	  kernel's canonical value, staleness flags, and effects are untouched. Its
  1466	  existence is visible only through overlay marks and to readers whose world
  1467	  includes its batch.
  1468	- An **urgent** write is logged *and applied*: the same call performs the
  1469	  normal kernel write (pending value, propagate, queue effects, collect
  1470	  broadcasts) and sets `APPLIED` on the record. This keeps the canonical
  1471	  world "committed plus urgent-pending" (the definition of W0), which is what
  1472	  non-render readers and core effects should see with zero replay work, and
  1473	  it means absorption of an urgent batch is usually a no-op fold.
  1474	
  1475	Consequence: the kernel's value for a logged atom always equals the fold of
  1476	its base record plus all APPLIED and all RETIRED-committed entries, in seq
  1477	order. This is the **W0 invariant**; absorption maintains it.
  1478	
  1479	### 9.5 Retirement and absorption
  1480	
  1481	When the fork reports `onBatchRetired(token, committed)`:
  1482	
  1483	1. Resolve the slot; bump `overlayEpoch` (world memos keyed on tape
  1484	   structure must re-validate — 10.5); stamp `RETIRED` + `RETIRED_SEQ =
  1485	   ticket()` on every entry of that batch, by iterating `loggedAtoms` and
  1486	   walking each tape (tapes are short; this is O(total live log entries), at
  1487	   commit frequency). The same walk performs absorption:
  1488	2. **Absorb**, per touched atom, inside one kernel `batch()`:
  1489	   - Recompute the W0 fold: replay from the base record, applying every
  1490	     entry that is RETIRED (any batch) or APPLIED-pending, in seq order.
  1491	     SET replaces the accumulator; UPDATE applies the stored function;
  1492	     DISPATCH applies the atom's reducer to the stored action. Updaters run
  1493	     once per world that includes them and must be pure — same contract as
  1494	     React updater functions.
  1495	   - If the fold differs from the kernel's current value (policy equality,
  1496	     section 11.2), write it through the kernel (`invalidate` + value set),
  1497	     which propagates staleness and queues core effects and
  1498	     `useSignalEffect` watchers.
  1499	   - Entries retired with `committed = false` (store-only batches that never
  1500	     made React work, including settled async actions) fold identically —
  1501	     the writes are real; the flag is recorded for tracing only. Dropping
  1502	     them would mean a `startTransition(() => atom.set(x))` with no
  1503	     subscribed component silently reverts — whether a user's write persists
  1504	     must never depend on who happened to be subscribed.
  1505	3. End the kernel batch → one effect flush for the whole absorption.
  1506	4. Decrement `unappliedEntries` for each formerly-unapplied entry; release
  1507	   batch slots per 9.2; then attempt a sweep (9.6).
  1508	
  1509	Replay ordering across batches is what produces React-parity rebasing: an
  1510	older transition's SET can never clobber a newer urgent SET, because the
  1511	urgent entry has a later seq and replays after it — worked example in 10.7.
  1512	
  1513	### 9.6 Sweeping and truncation
  1514	
  1515	An entry is **dead** once no possible reader can distinguish its presence:
  1516	it is RETIRED, and its `RETIRED_SEQ` is at or below every open pass's pin
  1517	(no pass is pinned before it), and it is not needed as replay input for a
  1518	still-pending entry earlier in the tape. The sweep (run at pass end,
  1519	retirement, and operation boundaries):
  1520	
  1521	- folds each atom's leading run of dead entries into the base record
  1522	  (`logVals[base] = fold; G[base+SEQ] = lastFolded.RETIRED_SEQ`), splicing
  1523	  the freed run onto the log free list in O(1);
  1524	- if the tape is just the base record and no live batch could still write
  1525	  (its batches all retired): free the tape entirely, clear
  1526	  `LOG_HEAD/LOG_TAIL` and the `LOGGED` flag, decrement `loggedAtomCount`,
  1527	  and remove the atom from `loggedAtoms`;
  1528	- drops world-memo records (10.5) whose world key names a retired batch, and
  1529	  trims memo chains opportunistically (memo validity is self-checking, so
  1530	  this is garbage hygiene, not correctness).
  1531	
  1532	**Truncation** is the abort primitive: `truncateBatch(slot)` unlinks every
  1533	entry of a batch from every tape *without folding*, fixing up chains and
  1534	counts, and bumps `overlayEpoch` (a mid-tape unlink changes world values
  1535	without moving any tail seq — memos must re-validate; 10.5). Nothing else is
  1536	needed to abandon speculation, because speculative writes never touched
  1537	canonical state. Exposed to policy for optimistic-update
  1538	rollback APIs and used by devtools; React batches themselves never truncate
  1539	(React always retires them).
  1540	
  1541	### 9.7 Quiescence: the bulk reset
  1542	
  1543	When `loggedAtomCount` reaches 0 with no open pass and no live slots:
  1544	
  1545	- plane G's bump pointer resets to 0 and its free list empties — the entire
  1728	## 10. View resolution
  1729	
  1730	### 10.1 Read contexts
  1731	
  1732	Every read resolves in one of four contexts. The context is a module scalar,
  1733	not a parameter — reads stay zero-argument bound calls.
  1734	
  1735	| context | active when | world |
  1736	| --- | --- | --- |
  1737	| `RENDER` | while React is *executing* render code: from `onRenderPassStart` to `onRenderPassEnd`, minus yield gaps (below) | Wp: pin + include mask |
  1738	| `NEWEST` | default: event handlers, timers, core effects, benchmarks, computed evaluation outside render — including all code running in a pass's yield gaps | Wn: everything visible |
  1739	| `COMMITTED` | inside `useSignalEffect` callbacks (and SSR) | the root's committed view (13.4); globally, retired entries only |
  1740	| kernel-internal | inside `checkDirty`/`update` walks | W0 by construction (the kernel only ever sees applied state) |
  1741	
  1742	**The scalar is kept correct by edges, including yields.** A time-sliced
  1743	pass stays *open* across yields to the event loop, but the code that runs in
  1744	those gaps — click handlers, timers, settled promises — is not render code:
  1745	its reads must resolve `NEWEST` (a handler deciding on a stale pinned world
  1746	would misbehave) and its writes must be legal (10.8 makes render-context
  1747	writes throw; an urgent write from a handler during a background render is
  1748	the design's flagship scenario, not an error). Since reads deliberately
  1749	never consult the fork, the bridge flips the context scalar on the fork's
  1750	yield/resume edges (6.3): `RENDER → NEWEST` at `onRenderPassYield`,
  1751	`NEWEST → RENDER` at `onRenderPassResume`. The pass set — pin, include mask,
  1752	serial, lineage — persists untouched across yields, so resumed render reads
  1753	still resolve the pass's world exactly. Debug builds assert
  1754	`getRenderContext() !== undefined` whenever a read actually runs in
  1755	`RENDER` context.
  1756	
  1757	### 10.2 The visibility rule
  1758	
  1759	For a pass with pin `P` and include mask `I`, a log entry `e` is **visible**
  1760	if and only if either:
  1761	
  1762	1. **It retired before the pass started:** `e.RETIRED` is set and
  1763	   `e.RETIRED_SEQ <= P`; or
  1764	2. **The pass includes its batch and the write predates the pass:**
  1765	   `I` has bit `e.BATCH_SLOT` and `e.SEQ <= P`.
  1766	
  1767	Each clause mirrors a rule React applies to its own hook queues: clause 2 is
  1768	the lane filter (a transition render applies transition updates and skips
  1769	urgent ones, and vice versa); the `<= P` conditions mirror React's rule that
  1770	updates arriving during a render are hidden from it and picked up by the
  1771	next one. Clause 1 keying on *retire time* rather than write time is what
  1772	keeps a paused-and-resumed pass stable: if another root commits (and folds)
  1773	while this pass is yielded, the fold's stamp exceeds this pass's pin, so this
  1774	pass keeps reading what it started with.
  1775	
  1776	`NEWEST` visibility: every entry. `COMMITTED` visibility, in its global
  1777	form: `RETIRED` entries only (regardless of stamps; APPLIED-but-pending
  1778	entries are *excluded*, which is what makes `useSignalEffect` observe only
  1779	committed worlds). Commits, however, are per root — a batch spanning two
  1780	roots commits on one while still pending on the other — so the bindings
  1781	refine `COMMITTED` into a **per-root committed view**: entries retired with
  1782	`RETIRED_SEQ` at or below the root's last-commit ticket, plus entries of
  1783	batches that root has committed while they stay pending elsewhere (the
  1784	fork's lock-in set, 6.2). Section 13.4 owns the mechanics; SSR and any
  1785	rootless committed read use the global form.
  1786	
  1787	**Writer's world** (used by broadcast, 10.6, and the post-subscribe fixup,
  1788	13.2): for a write in batch `B`, visibility is "RETIRED (any batch), or
  1789	APPLIED, or batch = B" — committed state plus urgent-pending plus the writing
  1790	batch's own entries. This is the world the batch's own render will show, so
  1791	it is the right world for deciding whether that render needs a component.
  1792	
  1793	### 10.3 Resolving an atom read
  1794	
  1795	```
  1796	readAtom(a):
  1797	  flags = M[a+FLAGS]
  1798	  if (flags & LOGGED) == 0: return kernelRead(a)      // the fast path
  1799	  head = M[a+LOG_HEAD]
  1800	  // shortcut: if every entry is visible and every visible entry is APPLIED
  1801	  // or absorbed, the kernel value IS the answer (common for urgent-only
  1802	  // activity): one pass over META words, no payload touched.
  1803	  if allVisibleAndApplied(head, ctx): return kernelRead(a)
  1804	  acc = logVals[head>>2]                               // base snapshot
  1805	  for rec in chain(head):
  1806	    if visible(rec, ctx):
  1807	      next = apply(rec, acc)    // SET: payload; UPDATE: fn(acc);
  1808	                                // DISPATCH: reducer(acc, action)
  1809	      acc = isEqual(acc, next) ? acc : next   // equality inside the fold,
  1810	                                              // preserving reference
  2008	that, plus log truncation, is the entirety of "abort" in this design.
  2009	
  2010	Suspense inside overlay evaluation uses the per-world thenable cache
  2011	(section 12.3) so promise identity is stable across replays of the same
  2012	world.
  2013	
  2014	### 10.6 Broadcast worlds (why watchers don't over- or under-notify)
  2015	
  2016	When a logged write propagates (urgent, via kernel) or is drained (deferred,
  2017	via the notify walk of 9.8), watchers subscribed to affected nodes must
  2018	decide whether to `setState`. The rule: a watcher broadcasts if and only if
  2019	its watched node's value **in the writer's world** (10.2) differs — by the
  2020	node's equality policy — from the last value it broadcast (or rendered) for
  2021	that world, memoized per world in the watcher's meta (`lastBroadcast`).
  2022	
  2023	Cost: one overlay evaluation of the watched node on the writer's world at
  2024	write time — work the imminent render would do anyway, and it prevents
  2025	render storms for equal-value writes (graph-level cutoff, matching the
  2026	kernel's own cutoff semantics). The evaluation is memoized **on the node**,
  2027	not the watcher (10.5, writer's-world key), so a thousand watchers of one
  2028	computed share one evaluation per drain; the per-watcher residue is an
  2029	equality compare against `lastBroadcast`. This memo-sharing is the designed
  2030	answer to wide fan-out on the write path, and the whole path is gated at
  2031	≤N× a DIRECT write (18.2).
  2032	
  2033	For unmarked nodes (no overlay anywhere below), the same rule runs without
  2034	overlay evaluation: the "evaluation" is the plain kernel read (which
  2035	pull-verifies through `checkDirty`), compared against `lastBroadcast` as
  2036	usual. The comparison is not skippable even here, because the broadcast
  2037	queue is filled at *possibly-stale* time — `propagate` enqueues watchers
  2038	before anyone knows whether the change survives the equality cutoff — and
  2039	`setVersion` always changes hook state, so an unconditional broadcast would
  2040	re-render on equal-value writes, the exact storm this section exists to
  2041	prevent.
  2042	
  2043	A third broadcast source joins these two: the drain's slot-chain
  2044	re-validation (9.8) broadcasts to watchers of nodes whose *pending-world*
  2045	value changed — nodes the canonical walk cannot reach when the dependency
  2046	exists only in that world. Those broadcasts run the same per-watcher cutoff,
  2047	against the same node-level memo, scheduled into the pending batch's lanes
  2048	via the entanglement API.
  2049	
  2050	### 10.7 Worked example: the rebase walkthrough
  2051	
  2052	State: `a = 1` (atom). A transition writes `a.update(x => x + 1)`; while it
  2053	is pending, an urgent click writes `a.update(x => x * 2)`.
  2054	
  2055	Tape after both writes (base seq 10):
  2056	
  2057	| record | op | batch | seq | applied | retired |
  2058	| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
  2059	| base | BASE `1` | — | 10 | — | yes (at 10) |
  2060	| e1 | UPDATE `x+1` | T (deferred) | 11 | no | no |
  2061	| e2 | UPDATE `x*2` | U (urgent) | 12 | yes | no |
  2062	
  2063	Kernel value (W0) = base + applied = `1*2 = 2`.
  2064	
  2065	- **Urgent render** (includes U, not T; pin 13): visible = base, e2 →
  2066	  `1*2 = 2`. The click's doubling shows; the transition stays invisible.
  2067	  React commits; U retires; e2 stamps RETIRED_SEQ 14. Absorption fold =
  2068	  base + retired(e2) + applied() = `2` — unchanged, no-op.
  2069	- **Transition render** (includes T; pin 15): visible = base,
  2070	  e1 (clause 2), e2 (clause 1, retired at 14 ≤ 15) → replay in seq order:
  2071	  `(1 + 1) * 2 = 4`. The transition lands *on top of* the urgent change.
  2072	- T retires: fold = `(1+1)*2 = 4`; kernel value moves 2 → 4 via
  2073	  `invalidate`; effects observe committed 4. Sweep folds everything into the
  2074	  base; tape frees; quiescence resets the overlay.
  2075	
  2076	`4` is exactly what two queued `useState` updaters produce in React — the
  2077	side-by-side `ReducerAtom`-vs-`useReducer` conformance test (17.6) pins this
  2078	equivalence across held-open transitions. Note the property that makes the
  2079	fold trustworthy: functional entries are never dropped or pre-evaluated —
  2080	they replay, in seq order, over whatever base the world provides. A design
  2081	that applied-and-discarded the urgent updater would fold T's retirement to
  2082	`1+1 = 2`... then re-apply nothing, committing 2 or 3 where React commits 4.
  2083	
  2084	### 10.8 Purity of render worlds
  2085	
  2086	Writes during `RENDER` context throw, unconditionally (React may replay or
  2087	discard the pass; a write from a replayed render would double-fire). This is
  2088	independent of `configure({ forbidWritesInComputeds })`, which governs
  2089	canonical evaluation contexts only.
