  2334	### 13.1 The watcher protocol
  2335	
  2336	A mounted `useSignal`/`useComputed` owns one **watcher node** (kind
  2337	`K_WATCHER`, flags `WATCHING|IMMEDIATE|LIVE`). Its `fns` entry is the
  2338	broadcast closure; its meta holds `lastBroadcast` per-world memos (10.6).
  2339	Watchers subscribe like effects — a link from the watched node — but notify
  2340	through the broadcast list, synchronously in the writer's stack:
  2341	
  2342	```
  2343	broadcast():  // called by the write wrapper's drain loop
  2344	  if worldValueChanged(watchedId, writerWorld):   // 10.6 cutoff
  2345	      setVersion(v => (v + 1) | 0)                // the hook's useState
  2346	```
  2347	
  2348	Because `setVersion` runs in the writer's context, React's
  2349	`requestUpdateLane` gives the re-render the writer's priority: transition
  2350	writes schedule transition re-renders, urgent writes schedule urgent
  2351	re-renders, updates inside async actions entangle — all inherited, never
  2352	reimplemented. Every signal-driven render passes through React's
  2353	infinite-loop guards (`NESTED_UPDATE_LIMIT`, render-phase re-render limit)
  2354	like any setState.
  2355	
  2356	### 13.2 `useSignal(signal)`
  2357	
  2358	Render phase (pure): read the signal in `RENDER` context (which resolves the
  2359	pass's world Wp) and return it. A mount *during* a transition render
  2360	therefore reads the pending world directly — no double render, no guessing;
  2361	this is the scenario stock-React userland provably cannot handle (the
  2362	known-bug test we inherit and turn green, 17.6). If the value is a
  2363	`SuspendedBox`, call React's `use(thenable)` — a conditional `use` is legal —
  2364	so Suspense fallbacks and replays behave exactly as for a suspending
  2365	`useState` initializer.
  2366	
  2367	Commit phase (layout effect): create/rebind the watcher node and link it to
  2368	the signal, then run the **post-subscribe fixup** for writes that raced into
  2369	the gap between render and subscription. The watcher remembers the world
  2370	(pin + include mask) and value it rendered with; both checks are
  2371	**world-aware** — they re-resolve the node and compare values, never
  2372	compare world identities, because "the committed value moved past what we
  2373	rendered" is *expected*, not a race, whenever the rendered world included a
  2374	still-pending batch (this component just rendered inside transition k's
  2375	pass; committed state excludes k by definition — a literal
  2376	committed-vs-rendered comparison would fire a spurious correction on every
  2377	such mount):
  2378	
  2379	- **Did this component's own world move?** Re-resolve the watched node in
  2380	  the watcher's remembered rendered world, *now*, and compare with the
  2381	  remembered value (by the node's equality). A difference means something
  2382	  raced into the gap that the rendered world would have shown — an urgent
  2383	  write, an absorption. Correct it with `setVersion` immediately, in the
  2384	  layout effect's own (urgent) context — a pre-paint correction, the same
  2385	  shape React uses for its own layout-effect updates. If the rendered
  2386	  world's batches have all retired (the world is no longer resolvable), the
  2387	  committed-value comparison is the correct degenerate form and is used as
  2388	  the fallback.
  2389	- **Did a pending world this component missed move?** For each live
  2390	  deferred batch slot whose tape entries affect the watched node, evaluate
  2391	  the node in that batch's writer's world (10.2, memoized per 10.5) and
  2392	  compare with the rendered value. For each batch where the value differs,
  2393	  issue the corrective `setVersion` through the fork's batch-entanglement
  2394	  API: `unstable_runInBatch(token, () => setVersion(bump))`. The correction
  2395	  is thereby assigned to the pending batch's own lanes — it renders with
  2396	  that batch and commits in that batch's frame (6.5). If `runInBatch`
  2397	  returns false, the batch retired between our check and the call; its
  2398	  values are already absorbed into committed state, so the first check
  2399	  covers it — the fixup re-runs the first comparison and falls back to that
  2400	  path.
  2401	
  2402	Why `startTransition` around the corrective setState would be wrong, and why
  2403	entanglement is required: a fresh `startTransition` mints a *new* batch with
  2404	its own lanes and its own commit. React would be free to commit the original
  2405	batch first — without this component's correction — and paint a frame where
  2406	sibling components show the transition's world and this component shows the
  2407	world it rendered a beat too early. The entangled update cannot exhibit that
  2408	frame: it is in the original batch's lanes, so that batch's render includes
  2409	it and that batch's single commit carries it. The test in 17.6 holds a
  2410	transition open, mounts a late subscriber, and asserts exactly one commit,
  2411	containing both the transition's updates and the correction.
  2412	
  2413	Both fixup checks compare against the watcher's remembered render world;
  2414	they fire only in genuine race windows. Unmount: unlink the watcher;
  2415	liveness sweeps run post-commit.
