  2417	### 13.3 `useComputed(fn, deps, options?)`
  2418	
  2419	A component-local `Computed` held in a `useState` holder, recreated when
  2420	`deps` change (compared like `useMemo`). `fn` closes over props/state freely
  2421	— that is exactly what `deps` re-creation handles; signal reads inside `fn`
  2422	are auto-tracked by the graph (in canonical contexts) and resolved per-world
  2423	during passes. Subscription and reads then work exactly like `useSignal` on
  2424	the local node. Disposal on unmount (and holder replacement) frees the
  2425	record deterministically.
  2426	
  2427	### 13.4 `useSignalEffect(fn, deps?)` and per-root committed views
  2428	
  2429	A passive-effect-scheduled graph watcher over **committed** state: the
  2430	callback runs after commit, reads in `COMMITTED` context, and re-runs when
  2431	(a) `deps` change (React pathway) or (b) the committed value of anything it
  2432	tracked changes (engine pathway, flushed in a microtask after the owning
  2433	root's commit — "after commit", matching `useEffect`'s contract). Cleanup
  2434	supported.
  2435	
  2436	"Committed" here is **per root**. Commits are per-root events: a batch
  2437	spanning two roots commits on root A while still pending on root B, and at
  2438	that moment root A's effects must see the batch's values (root A's DOM
  2439	already shows them — reading older state would put the effect behind its own
  2440	root's screen) while root B's effects must not (nothing committed there
  2441	yet). The global retired-only view can express neither side of that moment.
  2442	So the bridge keeps a small per-container table, updated on
  2443	`onBatchCommitted(container, token)` (6.1):
  2444	
  2445	- `committedPin[container]` — a fresh seq ticket taken at that root's
  2446	  commit; entries retired at or below it are in the root's committed view;
  2447	- `committedMask[container]` — the batch slots this root has committed while
  2448	  their tokens remain pending elsewhere (the bindings-side mirror of the
  2449	  fork's lock-in set, 6.2); entries of those batches are in the view too.
  2450	  When such a token finally retires everywhere, its slot bit clears and the
  2451	  pin advances past its retirement ticket — the view's contents are
  2452	  unchanged by that bookkeeping step.
  2453	
  2454	A `useSignalEffect` callback resolves reads against its own root's view, and
  2455	the engine-pathway flush runs per root commit, filtered by that root's view
  2456	— an effect re-runs when *its root's* committed world changed, not when any
  2457	token anywhere retired. SSR and rootless committed reads (a devtools dump,
  2458	say) use the global retired-only form (10.2). The table is a handful of
  2459	integers per live root, owned by the bindings; node records know nothing of
  2460	roots.
  2461	
  2462	### 13.5 `useAtom` / `useReducerAtom`
  2463	
  2464	Component-owned atoms: created in a `useState` initializer, disposed in the
  2465	unmount cleanup of an effect, recreated on strict-mode remount (the holder
  2466	pattern from the react-concurrent-store harness). They are ordinary atoms —
  2467	other components' computeds may read them through context or props.
  2468	
  2469	### 13.6 Transitions helpers
  2470	
  2471	`startSignalTransition(scope)` = `startTransition` + engine `batch()`: the
  2472	batch coalesces broadcasts so N writes notify each watcher once (one notify
  2473	walk ticket, one drain — 9.8). `useSignalTransition()` wraps `useTransition`
  2474	the same way; `isPending` is React's own. Neither is required for
  2475	correctness — plain `startTransition` works — they are throughput helpers.
  2476	
  2477	### 13.7 Multiple roots
  2478	
  2479	The engine keeps no per-root state beyond the current pass (one pass executes
  2480	at a time, 6.3). Batches spanning roots are correct by construction:
  2481	per-root commit lock-in lives in the fork's registry (6.2), which keeps
  2482	including a committed-elsewhere batch in that root's `includedBatches` until
  2483	the token retires everywhere; the engine just applies the mask it is given.
  2484	
  2485	### 13.8 SSR and hydration
  2486	
  2487	Server rendering uses `COMMITTED` context reads with no subscriptions and no
  2488	observed-lifecycle mounting (watcher creation is a layout-effect concern, and
  2489	layout effects don't run on the server). The write gate never activates on
  2490	the server — activation rides client root registration (9.1), and server
  2491	rendering registers none — so SSR stays DIRECT for the process's life and
  2492	pays zero overlay cost. No
  2493	`getServerSnapshot` analogue exists because reads are plain values. Flight/
  2494	RSC is out of scope for v1.
