   743	**Yield edges are protocol, not detail.** A time-sliced pass returns to the
   744	event loop *while remaining open*; user code — click handlers, timers,
   745	resolved promises — runs in those gaps. That is the whole point of
   746	concurrent rendering, and it means "a pass is open" and "we are executing
   747	render code right now" are different facts. The engine keeps a read-context
   748	scalar that must track the second fact (10.1), and it deliberately never
   749	consults the fork per read; so the fork delivers the transitions as edges:
   750	`onRenderPassYield` when the work loop's should-yield check makes it leave,
   751	`onRenderPassResume` when it re-enters. Both are wired where the work loop
   752	already knows it is leaving/re-entering; both are one null check when
   753	nothing subscribed. Without these two edges, a write from a click handler
   754	inside a yield gap would look like a render-phase write (which must throw,
   755	10.8) — the design's flagship scenario, an urgent update during a background
   756	render, would crash on first exercise.
   757	
   758	**Lineage names the work, not the pass.** React can restart a pass, and
   759	Suspense re-renders arrive as *new* passes when a promise settles. Anything
   760	cached "for this render" under a per-pass key would be discarded and
   761	re-created on every retry — for suspense caches that means re-fetching
   762	forever, never converging. And a single batch token under-identifies the
   763	work: a pass legitimately renders several entangled batches at once. So the
   764	fork assigns a **render lineage**: a serially-numbered integer minted when a
   765	root first schedules work for a given lane set, redelivered on every pass
   766	start for that same work — across yields, restarts, and Suspense retries —
   767	and retired when that work commits or is abandoned. Per-world suspense
   768	caches key on it (12.3).
   769	
   770	`includedBatches` contains the live tokens for the pass's render lanes plus
   771	the committed-elsewhere lock-ins from 6.2. Tokens whose batches carry no
   772	external writes are simply unknown to the engine and ignored.
